name: Compliance
contents:
Compliance

  • The volume change per unit change in pressure (ml.cmH20 or L.kPa)
  • is the measure of distensibility


Lung compliance - When adding compliance it is their reciprocals that are added (as with capacitance) so that :

  • 1/Ctotal = 1/Cchest + 1/Clung


  • Static compliance
  • The compliance of the lung measured when all gas flow has ceased.
  • lung compliance is best described using a pressure-volume loop under static conditions.
  • Dynamic compliance (lower than static compliance)
  • The compliance of the lung during the respiratory cycle when gas is still flowing
  • Airway resistance affects airflow
  • Incomplete filling of alveoli in available time
  • True pressure equilibrium between applied and alveolar pressure is not obtained

STATIC IS USUALLY HIGHER because there is time for volume and pressure equilibration between the lungs and the measuring system - the measured volume tends to increase and the measured pressure tends to decrease both of which act to increase compliance.


Resistance

  • Resistance - the pressure change per unit change in flow (cmH20.l-1) or kPa.l-1.sec-1)
  • Lung resistance - when adding resistances they are added as normal integers (as with electrical resistance). eg R = Chest wall + lung resistance


Time constant of a lung unit -

  • The product of compliance and resistance and a measure of how quickly the a lung unit will fill or empty. (or time taken to to inflate to 63% of its volume)


Measuring lung compliance

  • Compliance can be measured by inserting an oesophageal probe into a co-operative patient, the patient inhales and exhales to a set volume. At each volume the intrapleural pressure is estimated using the oesophageal probe. A pressure volume curve can then be plotted.
question3: How can you calculate the work of breathing
contents3:
Mechanical work of breathing: Force x distance

  • = Pressure x volume


Thus the work of breathing =

  • cumulative product of PRESSURE x VOLUME of air moved over time. (ie, the AUC) ie, over time integration.
  • = ∆P x ∆V/∆t


During quiet breathing most of the work preformed is required to overcome elastic resistance (65%) this inflates the lung and proves a store of elastic energy that gets released during expiration and is therefore viewed as useful work. However, overcoming non-elastic resistance (eg airway resistance and viscosity 35%) results in energy being dissipated as heat and is viewed as wasted work.

The normal metabolic cost of breathing is approximately 0.5-1.0ml/O2/L/min but this may increase to 2-4ml O2/L/min with hyperventilation.

Work increases with increasing TV, increasing respiratory flow and increasing airway resistance eg COPD.


Curve above - the area inside the smaller loop is wasted work.

  • Inspiration work - AGBCD (ie, outer loop)
  • Expiration work - BEADC (ie, inner)

Take the Inspiration - Expiration = wasted work - ie, the ellipse.
